{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503692"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:05:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:05:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2068"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2068"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.03,0.03,0.83,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2068"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81690"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2068"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2068"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66989"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1027"},{"type":"tags","id":"4939"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"5178"},{"type":"tags","id":"5180"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11691"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4204"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4205"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4379"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81690"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for counselling regarding a new medication. She has treatment-resistant depression and has not responded to three different antidepressant medications. She has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her psychiatrist is planning to commence tranylcypromine therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following foods should she be advised to avoid while taking this medication?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Eggs","Fresh fruit","White bread","Aged cheese","Fresh yoghurt"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question addresses the important dietary restrictions required when taking monoamine oxidase inhibitors (MAOIs). \u003Cstrong\u003EAged cheese\u003C/strong\u003E contains high levels of tyramine and must be avoided by patients taking irreversible MAOIs like tranylcypromine, as it can precipitate a dangerous hypertensive crisis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEggs\u003C/strong\u003E are safe to consume while taking MAOIs as they do not contain significant amounts of tyramine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFresh fruit\u003C/strong\u003E is generally safe to consume with MAOIs. While some overripe fruits may contain tyramine, fresh fruits do not pose a significant risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWhite bread\u003C/strong\u003E contains negligible amounts of tyramine and is safe to consume while taking MAOIs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFresh yoghurt\u003C/strong\u003E is safe to consume as it does not contain significant amounts of tyramine. However, aged or fermented dairy products should be avoided.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe interaction between tyramine-rich foods and MAOIs occurs because MAO-A normally breaks down dietary tyramine in the gut. When MAO-A is inhibited, tyramine enters the circulation and causes release of stored noradrenaline from nerve endings. This can lead to a dangerous surge in blood pressure. Other foods to avoid include cured meats, fermented soy products, and certain alcoholic beverages.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note that while this is an important and highly examinable interaction, recent evidence suggests that this risk has been eroded over time by changes in food production techniques that reduce the tyramine content. However, standard advice still applies to the use of these drugs and is listed on their warning labels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo important further caveats are also worth noting. Firstly, the reversible inhibitors of monoamine oxidase (RIMA agents) such as moclobemide largely avoid this problem because their action is reversible via competitive inhibition. Secondly, transdermal preparations of MAOIs have been shown to largely avert this problem because of decreased drug levels by the time it has circulated to the intestine.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EDuring hypertensive crisis, patients may complain of headache, sweating, agitation and chest pain. Complications may include an intracranial haemorrhage, rhabdomyolysis, acute renal failure and disseminated intravascular coagulation. Management of hypertensive crisis involves administration of vasodilator therapy such as sodium nitroprusside and glyceryl trinitrate as well as alpha-antagonists.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tyramine-containing foods can precipitate a hypertensive crisis in patients taking irreversible MAO inhibitors due to reduced breakdown of noradrenaline","Tranylcypromine is a non-selective irreversible MAO inhibitor used in treatment-resistant depression","Common tyramine-rich foods to avoid in patients taking MAO inhibitors include aged cheese, cured meats, and fermented products"],"references":["Calvi et al. Antidepressant Drugs Effects on Blood Pressure. Front Cardiovasc Med. 2021 Aug 3;8:704281. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34414219/","Gillman PK. A reassessment of the safety profile of monoamine oxidase inhibitors: elucidating tired old tyramine myths. J Neural Transm (Vienna). 2018 Nov;125(11):1707-1717. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30255284/","Stahl M (ed). Stahl\u0027s Essential Psychopharmacology. 4th ed, 2013. Cambridge University Press. ISBN 978-1-107-68646-5."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66989"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2068"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66989"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T19:56:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-26T19:56:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2068"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81690"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical s